info","should_display_ad_info":false},"serialized_frtp_identifiers":null,"debug_info":null,"inform_treatment_for_community_notes":null,"message":{"text":"Photos are an ideal way to preserve the past for future generations. For Save Your Photos Month, we\u2019re highlighting a scrapbook that was put together by the Admiral Perry Garst Auxiliary, which was part of the United Spanish War Veterans, group number 35. The auxiliary was a group that supported the veterans who had fought in the Spanish-American War. This scrapbook shows newspaper clippings of the activities the women participated in and hosted, and the ways they supported the veterans in their communities.\n\nScrapbooks evolved from the journals and diaries that people kept as early as the 7th century. These diaries were personal accounts of daily lives, and eventually these journals shifted from solely written to a combination of writing, drawings, and scraps of ephemera, like fabric, letters, and flowers. This started the type of scrapbooking that we know today: pieces of objects like newspapers and photographs used to tell a broader story to the reader. This scrapbook documents the various formal dinners, picnics, award ceremonies, and other community events that the auxiliary hosted in its efforts to highlight the actions of local veterans.\n\nPerry Garst was a rear admiral who was born in Dayton, Ohio. He served during the War and worked his way up the ranks, from captain of his own warship to rear admiral. While he was a captain, he commanded the U.S.S. \u2018Rhode Island\u2019 in 1906, and under him, the ship ran practice drills. His time on the ship was short, though, likely due to running the ship aground sometime during his service. He eventually became an instructor at the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis. Garst retired from the Navy in 1907 and eventually moved to Bradenton.\n\nScrapbook: 1998.012.1261\n\n#MustSeeInManatee #Collections #SpanishAmericanWar #Scrapbook
